My parliamentary colleague Joan Ryan was treated similarly because she opposed anti-Semitism.
In my case, the request for reprimand stemmed from a difference of opinion between me and Jeremy Corbyn.
The differences were about the importance of responsible economic policy, national security and Europe. Ironically, Jeremy Corbyn opposed the position of previous leaders on these issues.
In the announcement of Friday’s meeting of Labour MPs from Nottingham East district, it was read: “We want the meetings to be open and productive.”
During my eight years as Labour MP, most of the afternoon meetings of the General Committee on Fridays looked like this.
Unfortunately, many meetings are now held differently, and the promise of a “heartier and milder” policy has long been forgotten, as far as it has ever been remembered.
It is becoming increasingly clear that the Labour Party does not tolerate different views. Each opinion is evaluated in terms of compliance with the leadership of the party.
It all started shortly after Jeremy Corbyn took office as President, and my colleagues, who seemed to me to have similar views, began to expect me to change direction and take positions that I would not have agreed with before, such as national security or the EU single market.
After every public speech – regardless of the content – I meet on social media with attacks calling for the nomination to be withdrawn, the condemnation of centrism or the abandonment of the Labour Party.
This is not just my experience.
I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me are rather political in nature.
I admire the professionalism and determination of colleagues who experience sexist or racist treatment every day, but do not avoid further action.
One of the most disappointing aspects of the current policy is moving to the agenda with insulting others.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said the Labour Party should support a culture of tolerance.
In fact, we are no longer a group of people with different views. With every request for a “votum of mistrust” and every change in the rules of choice, the party’s worldview narrows down.
Over the past two years, I have been repeatedly told not to lean back and keep silent on certain issues, and then everything would be “okay”.
That’s not why I took up politics.
Since joining the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student as a result of Margaret Thatcher’s government’s negligence that led to the disintegration of my school class, I have been trying to ensure a better quality of public service for those in need – both as a local councilor and as a minister.
I never hid my beliefs, even during the last election campaign.
Everyone in Nottingham East knew my position and knew the differences of opinion with the party authorities.
To those who supported Friday's proposal, I would like to say that I cannot understand the willingness to waste my time and energy on the issue of my loyalty to the Labour leader in the face of the impending Brexit that will harm households, businesses and public services.
However, the most important message I send not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents (both members of the Labour Party and others): I am proud to be of service to you. I promise that no threat of revocation or imminent political objectives will discourage me from acting in accordance with my convictions and in the best interest of all of you.
Chris Leslie is an MP from Nottingham East.
