“The sea belongs to us”: Bolivia, deprived of access to the sea, hopes that the court will reopen its way to the Pacific
Marines patrol the vicinity of the naval base in La Paz.
Blue flags are flying from public buildings.
In the ports of the navy, from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the motto reads: “The sea is ours by law.
It is our duty to take him back.”
In a landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in a bloody 19th-century resource conflict is still alive, like a dream of sailing the Pacific Ocean again.
These hopes are perhaps the highest in decades. Bolivia awaits the judgment of the International Court of Justice. It is due to be delivered on 1 October after a five-year trial.
“Bolivia’s actions are gaining momentum. The people are unanimous, optimistic and hope for a favorable verdict,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians across the country will watch the International Court of Justice together, hoping that the Hague-based organization will recognize Bolivia's claim and that after decades of fruitless talks Chile will have to negotiate to give the state independent access to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic president who will face a controversial re-election battle next year, also hopes for Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he vowed at the end of August.
However, some analysts say that the chances of a positive decision for Bolivia are small and that even a favorable decision would not change much.
The United Nations body based in The Hague does not have the authority to grant Bolivia Chilean territory, and it has also stated that it will not affect the arrangements for possible talks.
As Paz Z<0xC3><0xA1>rate, Chilean specialist in international law, said, the decision of the International Court of Justice will be issued six months after the final arguments have been presented. Such a short time shows that the case "was not complicated".
Unfortunately for Bolivia, the last four years may have pushed the country away from its goal.
“The issue of access to the sea has been seized by the current Bolivian administration,” Paz Z<0xC3><0xA1>rate said.
Morales’ relentless rhetoric deprived the Chileans of any remnants of goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but this will be very difficult in the face of the situation.
There has been no exchange of ambassadors between the two countries since 1962.
Eduardo Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Veltzé, the former President and representative of Bolivia in The Hague, disagreed with the opinion that the court’s decision-making process was extremely fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia "a unique opportunity to start a new era in relations with Chile" and an opportunity to "end a 139-year period of disputes with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales — still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — used the topic of access to the sea as part of the political game.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The ruling is a great opportunity to see that we have to deal with the past.”
