John Edward: Language Skills Necessary for World Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their scientific achievements – in 2018 they were able to boast of further excellent exam results, supported by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other social ventures.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), the schools with more than 30,000 students across Scotland aim to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career path and to indicate their role as global citizens.
As an educational sector with the ability to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another person in a language that he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that languages occupy the first place in the league rankings, with the highest susceptibility rates in the case of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a higher A score.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received a higher A score in Mandarin, and 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also received an A score.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, the teaching of languages as subjects of choice is conducted in the same scope as the teaching of STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the framework of curricula in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of job vacancies were due to a lack of candidates’ language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people to start a career.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with an increasing number of jobs requiring language skills.
A lifelong skill, like learning a second language, will provide a huge advantage in the future, regardless of the career path you choose.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person compared to the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults, 75% of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit, 15%, percentage.
That is why investing in foreign language teaching is so important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages it teaches.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of the child, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from, which will be taught by the specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed – no matter what the future holds for them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment languages are still crucial for the future of the country, and so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be treated as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a great choice, diversity and level.
That's just the way it should be.
John Edward, Chairman of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
