North Korea says “definitely not” to unilateral disarmament without trust.
North Korea's foreign minister said on Saturday at the United Nations that the failure to lift sanctions only deepens North Korea's lack of trust in the United States and there is no way the country will unilaterally abandon nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site of nuclear tests, and committing to non-proliferation of weapons and nuclear technology.
"We do not see any specific response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no guarantee of our national security, and under such circumstances, there is no way to unilaterally disarm North Korea.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known grievances about Washington’s reluctance to take a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded for taking action gradually, his statement seemed significant because it did not reject unilateral denuclearization, as it has in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the incumbent U.S. President and North Korean leader, which took place on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim Jong Un pledged to work for the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” and Trump promised security guarantees for Korea.
North Korea expected a formal end to the Korean War (from 1950 to 1953), but the U.S. delegation announced that Pyongyang must first abandon nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a forced manner, even opposing the signing of a 'declaration of an end to the war,'" Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a mockery of people who behave ignorantly towards us.
The problem, however, is that the failure to lift sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, which the U.S. leader spoke about earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, after which he added: “If South Korea were the party to the denuclearization issue, and not the United States, then there would be no such impasse in the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula.”
Meanwhile, Ri’s tone of speech was completely different from last year, when he said at the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles in the United States was inevitable after Trump’s “Mr. Evil President” called Kim Jong Un a “rocket man.”
At the UN this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim Jong Un for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but also said there was still a lot of work to be done, and said that until North Korea is stripped of its nuclear weapons, sanctions will not be lifted.
Trump said on Wednesday that he did not set a timeframe for this, saying, “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that “enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue and be ongoing until we have found complete, definitive and verified denuclearization.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea in an attempt to stifle funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly forum and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month in preparation for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit is not a success.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, and within hours North Korea condemned him for “placing gangster demands.”
North Korea pledged this month at a meeting with Moon Jae-in to dismantle a missile test site and a nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim Jong Un had told him that the “appropriate measures” he cared about were the security guarantees Trump had pledged in Singapore and steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on long-term rest.
A new course at Harvard University, which took place this year, provided all students with more sleep, aimed at combating the growing macho culture of being taught by “all-night caffeine-driven students.”
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
To create the course, he was inspired by a speech about the impact of sleep deprivation on science.
“At the end of the speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now that I’m in my final year of college?’
She stated that no one had ever told her about the meaning of the dream, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
During the course, which was held for the first time this year, it is explained to students how good sleep habits help to achieve good results in learning and sports, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health service, said the course was set to be introduced after it was found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes an image of a dorm room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise, and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, as well as how important it is to keep your sleep regular.
In another section, participants learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not lead to an immediate change in students’ behaviour.
But we believe that they have a right to know — just as everyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking.”
A culture of pride in “all-night science” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean an increasing problem of sleep deprivation.
Ensuring enough good quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, making the student constantly hungry, he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course after taking one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the introduction of the course for the entire campus.
According to him, the next step is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar program of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm to remind them when to go to sleep and when to get up, as well as to be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic devices screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and lead to problems with falling asleep.
