Almanac: inventor of the Geiger counter
And now the page from our Sunday Morning edition of Almanac: September 30, 1882 — 136 years ago... the day the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, which eventually led to the creation of a device known as the Geiger counter.
Since then, the Geiger counter has become both a part of science and pop culture, as in the 1950 film Bells of Coronado, in which these seemingly unlikely cowboy-scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans starred:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: “This is a Geiger counter used to locate radioactive minerals such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you will hear the effects of the atoms emitted by the radioactive minerals.”
Evans: “Now you hear something!”
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name has survived to this day.
