The creator of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet in order to compete with Google and Facebook platforms.
Tim Berners-Lee, creator of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is an open-source platform company — Solid — owned by Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have access to specific information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal of creating Inrupt was to “dominate the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said, referring to the startup.
“The historic moment has arrived.”
The app uses Solid platform technology to enable people to create their own “personal data online store” or POD.
It can include contact lists, do-it-yourself lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify available in one browser and at the same time.
A unique feature of the online store with personal data is that it is completely up to the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is to provide resources, processes and the right skills to help make the Solid platform available to all people.
Currently, the company includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers working on the project, and a community of volunteer developers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world were able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about whether to make a complete change that will turn all their business models upside down from day to day.
“I don’t ask for permission.”
Berners-Lee wrote in a Wednesday post on Medium that “Inrupt’s mission is to deliver commercial energy and ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been much involved in the debate on net neutrality.
Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely excited to be thinking about the next era in network development,” Berners-Lee added.
