The memory of the only clergyman of the Church of England, who was awarded the Victoria Cross during World War I as a combatant, was celebrated 100 years later in his hometown.
Lt. Col. Bernard Vann was honoured on 29 September 1918 for his assault on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later, never knowing that he had been awarded the highest British military order.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren unveiled a memorial stone during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandsons, Michael Vann, said the stone’s unveiling on the centenary of his grandfather’s award was “extraordinarily symbolic.”
On September 29, 1918, Lt. Col. Vann led his battalion through the Canal Saint-Quentin "in very dense fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns".
Then he hastened to the line of fire and with "the greatest courage" led her forward, after which alone he launched an attack on the position of the field units, neutralizing three of them.
Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I could never handle, but at the same time something humble.”
Together with his brother, Dr. James Vann, he laid the wreath after the end of the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he felt "very honored to be able to participate in the parade" and added that "the courage of a true hero is manifested in the support he receives from many people."
