National Trust eavesdrops on the secret life of bats
A new study on the Highlands estate in Scotland aims to show how bats use the landscape to get food.
The findings are expected to shed new light on the behaviour of these exceptional flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study, led by researchers from the National Trust for Scotland, will look at common and small dwarfs, as well as brown bats with long ears and bats from the Red Nights family at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
In key locations around the property, special recorders will be deployed to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct field research using portable detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all recordings is aimed at determining the frequency of signals sent by bats and the behavior of individual species.
Then, a habitat map and report will be developed to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation adviser, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, such as meadow formation, as well as the best ways to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are at risk of construction and development work, which have an impact on ridges and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as well as fly glue and some chemicals used in building materials, and even domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to night hunting habits, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to search for worms and obstacles on their way.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land nationwide, takes bats very seriously.
It consists of ten trained experts who regularly carry out tests, inspections of the bays, and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization even established the first and only dedicated bat reserve in Scotland on the Threeve estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
David Thompson, the landlord, says it's an ideal territory for bats.
“Threave has a great area for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and excellent habitats.
However, there are still a lot of unknowns when it comes to bats, and the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
It highlights the importance of controlling for bats before proceeding with maintenance work on the estates, as the unintentional destruction of one rod can kill up to 400 females and young, which can lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected — killing, harassing, or disturbing them, as well as destroying their perimeter is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many species, we don’t even know how their populations are doing.”
