What the economic war between the United States and China can bring to Beijing
The salvos starting the economic war between the U.S. and China have been staggering, and while the battle is still ongoing, in the long run, the conflict between these countries could be beneficial for Beijing, experts say.
The first warning was issued this year by U.S. President Donald Trump, imposing tariffs on key Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week after the introduction of new tariffs on goods worth $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion), which resulted in the taxation of half of all goods coming to the United States from China.
Each time, Beijing reciprocated in nature, recently raising tariffs on US goods worth $60 billion from five percent to ten percent.
China is determined to respond to every U.S. strike, and it doesn’t look like the world’s second economy is about to give up.
Forcing Washington to back down means accepting the demands, but publicly bowing your head to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
According to experts, if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressure from the trade war with the United States could strengthen China in the long run, reducing the dependence between the two economies.
