Foreign Minister Says Syria Is ‘Ready’ to Return Refugees
The government says Syria is ready for the voluntary return of refugees, and is asking for help in rebuilding a country devastated by more than seven years of war.
In a speech to the UN General Assembly, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that conditions in the country were improving.
“The situation on our soil is now more stable and safer thanks to progress in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
In an effort to restore normality, the government is constantly rebuilding areas destroyed by terrorists.
All conditions have already been met so that refugees who had to leave the country because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and means of subsistence can voluntarily return to it.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million people have left Syria since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people who still live there need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to accept assistance in rebuilding the destroyed country.
However, he stressed that he would not accept the aid provided by the conditions or offered by the countries that sponsored the rebellion.
