Information about the bloom — in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota the density of plankton decreases
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decline in plankton density in some parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, the presence of variegated inflorescence has been reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting that its density is decreasing.
It stretches over a length of about 209 kilometers of coastline, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
Blooms can be found about 16 kilometers off the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
The bloom was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations of plankton were recorded in the County of Pinellas, low to medium in the County of Hillsborough, natural to high in the County of Manatee, natural to high in the County of Sarasota, natural to medium in the County of Charlotte, and natural to high in the County of Cololas.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
However, they were not recorded in Northwest Florida last week.
